## Formal System in Mathematical Logic

The [simply typed lambda calculus](/Type_theory) (&#8288;&#955;<sup>&rarr;</sup>&#8288;), a rather elegant, if somewhat austere, interpretation of the [lambda calculus](/Lambda_calculus), operates with a singular [type constructor](/Type_constructor): the arrow, &rarr; (&#8288;&rarr;&#8288;), which, with a certain ruthless efficiency, builds [function types](/Function_type). It stands as the quintessential, the most basic, example of a typed lambda calculus. This system, the simply typed lambda calculus, was brought into the world by [Alonzo Church](/Alonzo_Church) himself back in 1940. His motivation? To build a logical fortress against the paradoxes that threatened to consume the [untyped lambda calculus](/Untyped_lambda_calculus).&#91;1&#93;

The term "simple type" itself can be a bit of a chameleon, extending to encompass variations of the simply typed lambda calculus that incorporate features like [products](/Cartesian_product), [coproducts](/Coproduct), or even the seemingly innocuous [natural numbers](/Natural_number) (as seen in [System T](/Dialectica_interpretation)), or the full, untamed force of [recursion](/Recursion) (like in the [Programming Language for Computable Functions, PCF](/Programming_language_for_Computable_Functions)). In stark contrast, systems that dare to introduce [polymorphic types](/Parametric_polymorphism) (such as [System F](/System_F)) or the intricate architecture of [dependent types](/Dependent_type) (like the [Logical Framework](/LF_(logical_framework))) are generally not considered "simply typed." The reason for this distinction? The "simple types," barring the absolute surrender to full recursion, can still be rendered using just the &rarr; constructor and a judicious deployment of type variables. Polymorphism and dependency, however, are a different beast entirely.

### Syntax

Back in the fervent intellectual climate of the 1930s, [Alonzo Church](/Alonzo_Church) was wrestling with what he termed the "logistic method."&#91;a&#93; His [lambda calculus](/Lambda_calculus), conceived as a formal language built from symbolic expressions, was a labyrinth of denumerably infinite axioms and variables.&#91;b&#93; Yet, it was also a meticulously crafted system of a finite set of primitive symbols,&#91;c&#93; denoting abstraction and scope. This was augmented by four fundamental constants: negation, disjunction, universal quantification, and selection,&#91;d&#93;&#91;e&#93; alongside a finite set of rules, I through VI. Among these, rule V, the venerable [modus ponens](/Modus_ponens), and rules IV and VI for substitution and generalization, were particularly crucial.&#91;d&#93; Rules I to III, for those who’ve dared to venture into this territory, are known as alpha, beta, and eta conversion within the lambda calculus. Church’s intent was for English to serve merely as a syntax language—a metamathematical stage—for describing these symbolic expressions, devoid of any inherent interpretations.&#91;f&#93;

By 1940, Church had settled on a subscript notation to meticulously denote the type of each symbolic expression.&#91;b&#93; In his original formulation, he employed only two base types: &#8288;`o`&#8288; for "the type of propositions" and &#8288;`&iota;`&#8288; for "the type of individuals." The type &#8288;`o`&#8288; was starkly devoid of term constants, while &#8288;`&iota;`&#8288; had just one. Often, the calculus is considered with a single base type, typically &#8288;`o`&#8288;. Greek letters like &#8288;&alpha;&#8288;, &#8288;&beta;&#8288;, and so on, were used as type variables; the parenthesized subscript &#8288;(&alpha;&#946;)&#8288; denoted the function type &#8288;&beta; &rarr; &alpha;&#8288;. Church, in his 1940 paper (p. 58), employed the "arrow or &rarr;" notation to signify "stands for," or more accurately, as an abbreviation for it.&#91;g&#93; By the 1970s, the standalone arrow notation had become commonplace; in this context, symbols like &#8288;&sigma;&#8288; and &#8288;&tau;&#8288; are permitted to range over types. The infinite array of axioms was then understood as a consequence of applying rules I to VI to these types, echoing the structure of the [Peano axioms](/Peano_axioms). Informally, the function type &#8288;&sigma; &rarr; &tau;&#8288; represents the type of functions that accept an input of type &#8288;&sigma;&#8288; and produce an output of type &#8288;&tau;&#8288;.

By convention, the &rarr; symbol is right-associative: &#8288;&sigma; &rarr; &tau; &rarr; &rho;&#8288; is interpreted as &#8288;&sigma; &rarr; (&tau; &rarr; &rho;)&#8288;.

To formally define these types, we first establish a [set](/Set_(mathematics)) of base types, denoted by &#8288;B&#8288;. These are sometimes referred to as atomic types or type constants. With &#8288;B&#8288; fixed, the syntax of types follows this recursive definition:

&#8288;&tau; ::=&tau; &rarr; &tau; | T &#8288; where &#8288; T &isin; B.&#8288;

For instance, if &#8288;B = {a, b}&#8288;, this generates an infinite hierarchy of types, beginning with &#8288;a&#8288;, &#8288;b&#8288;, then &#8288;a &rarr; a&#8288;, &#8288;a &rarr; b&#8288;, &#8288;b &rarr; b&#8288;, &#8288;b &rarr; a&#8288;, and progressing to more complex forms like &#8288;a &rarr; (a &rarr; a)&#8288;, and even &#8288;(b &rarr; a) &rarr; (a &rarr; b)&#8288;, and so forth.

A set of term constants is also designated for these base types. For example, if one of the base types is designated as `nat`, its term constants might be the natural numbers themselves.

The syntax of the simply typed lambda calculus is, in essence, the syntax of the lambda calculus itself. The notation &#8288;x : &tau;&#8288; signifies that the variable &#8288;x&#8288; possesses type &#8288;&tau;&#8288;. The term syntax, expressed in [Backus–Naur form](/Backus%E2%80%93Naur_form), encompasses variable references, abstractions, applications, or constants:

&#8288;e ::= x | &lambda;x : &tau;. e | e e | c&#8288;

where &#8288;c&#8288; represents a term constant. A variable reference &#8288;x&#8288; is considered "bound" if it falls within the scope of an abstraction that binds &#8288;x&#8288;. A term is deemed "closed" if it contains no unbound variables.

In stark contrast, the syntax of the untyped lambda calculus dispenses with such typing and term constants altogether:

&#8288;e ::= x | &lambda;x. e | e e&#8288;

The crucial difference lies in the typed lambda calculus: every abstraction, that is, every function, is compelled to declare the type of its argument.

### Typing Rules

To precisely define the set of well-typed lambda terms for any given type, we establish a typing relation. This relation operates within typing contexts, also known as [typing environments](/Typing_environment), denoted by &#8288;&Gamma;, &Delta;, ...&#8288;. These contexts are essentially sets of typing assumptions. A typing assumption takes the form &#8288;x : &sigma;&#8288;, asserting that the variable &#8288;x&#8288; belongs to type &#8288;&sigma;&#8288;.

The typing relation &#8288;&Gamma; &vdash; e : &sigma;&#8288; signifies that &#8288;e&#8288; is a term of type &#8288;&sigma;&#8288; within the context &#8288;&Gamma;&#8288;. When this relation holds, &#8288;e&#8288; is considered "well-typed" (possessing type &#8288;&sigma;&#8288;). Instances of this typing relation are termed typing judgments. The validity of a typing judgment is demonstrated by a typing derivation, a structured argument built using [typing rules](/Typing_rule), where the premises positioned above a line logically lead to the conclusion below it. The simply typed lambda calculus employs these specific rules:&#91;h&#93;

